sec.p:
A connection has been documented between body size and key biological attributes such as basal metabolism, reproductive rate, mortality, and population abundance, known as allometric relationships or scaling laws11–14. Mathematically, this relationship can be expressed as: \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$Y=\xi \cdot m^{\alpha }$$\end{document}, where Y represents one of these biological attributes, \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\xi$$\end{document} is a species-specific factor, m denotes body size, and \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\alpha$$\end{document} is the allometric exponent15–18. Scaling relationships that describe variations in population density within ecological communities, such as the thinning law in plant ecology19, can be explained by observing how individuals of different sizes utilize available resources20. Data on xylem transport rates relative to stem diameter show that resource consumption rates in individual plants follow an approximate scale of \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\alpha =3/4$$\end{document} relative to body mass, similar to metabolic rates in animals21. These relationships enable the integration of biological aspects into models that represent trophic chain dynamics, simulated through ordinary differential equations22–25. This approach is particularly relevant to plant–insect interactions, given the complexities of these systems26–29. To achieve a better understanding of emerging complexities, the patterns proposed in the Metabolic Theory of Ecology11 and mathematical modeling help establish relationships between body sizes, providing a clearer perspective on system structure. In a tritrophic system, three distinct techniques are available for measuring body size. In this study, to standardize these measurements, plant size is associated with leaf area30, while the body size of the pest and its control organism can be expressed in grams or length using the allometric cube law31.

In this study, we present a tritrophic model represented by a system of differential equations, whose parameters depend on species’ body sizes. Our research aims to address three fundamental questions: Which relationships between species’ body sizes limit population densities and prevent coexistence? What body size relationships ensure the success of biological control? How can the trophic cascade effect be modeled as a function of body size, and how can it impact indirectly plants? These questions aim to deepen our understanding of the role of body size in shaping ecological interactions and the effectiveness of biological control strategies. To address the first question, we explore the conditions under which the model generates bounded density trajectories, determine equilibrium points, and analyze system stability. In this context, stability is understood as the ability of the plant–pest-biological control system to withstand disturbances and maintain its structure and function over time, either by returning to an equilibrium state (resilience) or remaining within certain dynamic limits (persistence). To answer the second question, we derive a biological indicator from the modeled system, denoted as \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathscr {R}{0}$$\end{document}, which primarily depends on body sizes. This parameter is analogous to the basic reproductive number in epidemiology and, in the context of plant–pest biological control, represents the predator’s ability to produce offspring throughout its lifetime after being introduced into a stable prey population. If \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathscr {R}{0} < 1$$\end{document}, both the biological control agent and the pest population will eventually disappear; conversely, if \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathscr {R}_{0} > 1$$\end{document}, both will persist in the system39. Finally, to evaluate the impact of biological control on plants, we consider previous theoretical ecology studies suggesting that the indirect effects of predators on basal resources may depend on body size40. We model the trophic cascade effect to identify which body sizes exert greater pressure on plants and how these effects influence system dynamics.

