				\begin{document}$$\beta = 0.5$$\end{document}. This formulation ensures that the larger organism plays a dominant role in determining the scaling of the encounter rate.

The consumption threshold \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$H_0(m_Y, m_X)$$\end{document} represents the saturation point at which a specialist predator can no longer increase its consumption rate, even when the prey abundance is high. This threshold is calculated using the expression:4\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} H_{0}(m_{Y},m_{X}) = \frac{h_{0} \cdot m_{Y}^{\alpha _{Y}-1}}{e_{Y} \cdot \frac{m_{X}}{m_{Y}} \cdot \Phi (m_{Y},m_{X})}, \end{aligned}$$\end{document}where \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$h_0$$\end{document} is a proportionality constant independent of body size. \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$m_Y$$\end{document} and \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$m_X$$\end{document} represent the predator and prey body sizes, respectively. \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\alpha _Y$$\end{document} is the allometric exponent associated with the metabolic rate, while \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$e_Y$$\end{document} denotes a factor related to the efficiency of converting prey biomass into predator biomass. When the consumer is much smaller than the resource (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$m_Y \ll m_X$$\end{document}), the ratio \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\frac{m_Y}{m_X}$$\end{document} tends to zero, making the exponential term in \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\Phi$$\end{document} negligible. In this case, the interaction function simplifies to\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} \Phi (m_Y, m_X) \approx \left( 1 - e^{-(\frac{m_Y}{m_X})^2}\right) \cdot \left[ f_0\, m_X^{\beta } + f_\infty \, m_Y^{\beta } \right] \approx 0, \end{aligned}$$\end{document}indicating very low capture efficiency. This implies that consumers with significantly smaller body sizes than their resources are biomechanically or sensorily constrained, leading to a negligible per capita feeding rate, even when resources are abundant.

Conversely, when the consumer is much larger than the resource (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$m_Y \gg m_X$$\end{document}), the exponential term tends to one, and the function \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\Phi$$\end{document} approaches to\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} \Phi (m_Y, m_X) \approx f_0\, m_X^{\beta } + f_\infty \, m_Y^{\beta } \approx f_\infty \, m_Y^{\beta }, \end{aligned}$$\end{document}as the contribution of the prey’s body size becomes negligible. This reflects high capture efficiency, consistent with empirical observations that larger consumers are more effective predators or foragers.

Regarding the effect of resource availability, when the resource density is much lower than the saturation threshold (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$X \ll H_0$$\end{document}), the functional response is approximately linear in R, since the denominator in the expression approaches 1. Thus,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} f(X) \approx \Phi (m_Y, m_X) \cdot X, \end{aligned}$$\end{document}characterising the unsaturated regime in which consumption increases proportionally with resource abundance. In contrast, when the resource density greatly exceeds the saturation threshold (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$X \gg H_0$$\end{document}), the functional response reaches an asymptotic maximum. This is evident in the limit:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} \lim _{X \rightarrow \infty } f(X)&= \lim _{X \rightarrow \infty } \frac{\Phi (m_Y, m_X) \cdot X}{1 + \frac{X}{H_0(m_Y, m_X)}} = \Phi (m_Y, m_X) \cdot H_0(m_Y, m_X) \\ &\quad \cdot \lim _{X \rightarrow \infty } \frac{X}{X + H_0} = \Phi (m_Y, m_X) \cdot H_0(m_Y, m_X). \end{aligned}$$\end{document}which defines the maximum per capita intake rate. This value is jointly determined by the efficiency of encounter and capture, encoded in \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\Phi (m_Y, m_X)$$\end{document}, and the body-size-dependent saturation threshold \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$H_0(m_Y, m_X)$$\end{document}. Biologically, this saturation arises from constraints in handling, digestion, or processing that limit the consumer’s ability to exploit additional resources, even under conditions of high resource availability. This efficiency is modulated by the ratio \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\frac{m_X}{m_Y}$$\end{document}, which describes the size relationship between predator and prey and influences predation efficiency, as seen in Fig. 1.Fig. 1
