In order to analyse the plant–pest-biological control system using theoretical tools, we introduce the model (1). In this system, the solutions represent species abundances over time and can be described within the mathematical space defined as \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathbb {R}^3_+ = \{(R, C, P) \in \mathbb {R}^3: R \ge 0, C \ge 0, P \ge 0\}$$\end{document}. The model has been formulated to ensure the existence and uniqueness of abundance trajectories, which is achieved, from a technical perspective, through the mathematical property of Lipschitz continuity. This property guarantees that the system’s rate of change remains smooth, preventing singularities in population dynamics. A fundamental requirement for the model to accurately describe the ecological system is that its solutions remain within a bounded range, meaning that species abundances do not diverge to infinity. This behaviour is ensured by establishing that the positive octant of \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathbb {R}^3_+$$\end{document} is an invariant region. Ecologically, this implies that despite population fluctuations, the system tends to stabilise within a set of viable values. The ecological conditions that ensure bounded solutions are determined by energy conversion efficiencies, which are expressed through the inequalities \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
