To study the equilibrium densities, we first set the derivatives of the abundances in model (1) equal to zero. By doing this, we obtain an algebraic system of equations, which, when solved, provides the expressions for the equilibrium densities, which, in this case, are five. Once the equilibrium densities are obtained, the next step is to study their stability. In this context, local stability refers to how the abundances behave near the equilibrium point. Local stability allows us to determine whether, in the face of small perturbations, the system will return to equilibrium or move away from it, leading the system to a new state. If the system returns to equilibrium after a disturbance, the equilibrium is considered stable; if it moves away, the equilibrium is unstable. To evaluate this stability, we focus on a small neighborhood around the equilibrium and analyze the system’s behavior in that region. This approach, known as local stability analysis, was proposed by Henri Poincaré in 1886. The model (1) admits a set of equilibrium points, denoted as \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$E_0, E_1, E_2, E_3$$\end{document}, and \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$E_4$$\end{document}, whose expressions are presented below. Each equilibrium corresponds to a specific ecological configuration, and the signs and mathematical expressions carry biological significance. The state \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
