				\begin{document}$$e_{C} \cdot m_{R} \cdot H_{0}(m_{C},m_{R}) \cdot \Phi (m_{C},m_{R}) > \delta _{C} \cdot m_{C}^{\alpha _{C}}$$\end{document}. The left side of the inequality represents the pest’s ability to acquire resources, which increases with the amount of available resources and the efficiency of the consumers. On the other hand, the right side reflects the metabolic cost associated with the pest’s body size; as its size increases, so does its resource demand, which raises competition and can reduce the availability of resources for the pest. In other words, the equilibrium will be positive if the consumers’ ability to access and utilize resources exceeds the metabolic expenditure associated with their size and demand.

By simplifying, it is possible to obtain more manageable expressions for these equilibria. In particular, if the relationship between the body size of the pest and that of the plant is optimal23, then \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
