				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$m_{C}$$\end{document}, thus recovering the allometric relationships reported in empirical studies18. These equilibrium density patterns for plants and pests remain valid within the parameter space, provided that cycles do not occur46,47. Without biological control, model (1) reduces to a system of two differential equations, where the equilibrium can be either stable or unstable. In the unstable case, this equilibrium is surrounded by a unique stable limit cycle, which acts as a global attractor. Technically, the transition between these two regimes is determined by a complex relationship between body sizes (through a Hopf bifurcation) and can eventually be tested in empirical investigations. The mathematical relationship is given by:11\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} & \frac{K\cdot m_{R}^{\gamma _{R}}}{H_{0}(m_{C},m_{R})}\cdot \left[ e_{C} \cdot \frac{m_{R}}{m_{C}}\cdot H_{0}(m_{C},m_{R}) \cdot \Phi (m_{C},m_{R})-\delta _{C} \cdot m_{C}^{\alpha _{C}-1}\right] \nonumber \\ & \quad = e_{C} \cdot \frac{m_{R}}{m_{C}}\cdot H_{0}(m_{C},m_{R}) \cdot \Phi (m_{C},m_{R}) + \delta _{C} \cdot m_{C}^{\alpha _{C}-1}. \end{aligned}$$\end{document}Although a detailed bifurcation analysis of lies beyond the scope of this study, it is relevant to consider that body size affects not only consumption rates or metabolism, but also the qualitative dynamics of the system. An ecologist might infer that certain morphological combinations between species. For example, a biological control agent that is either too large or too small relative to its prey can induce cyclic instabilities rather than maintain a stable population equilibrium. This may result in outbreaks and collapses, which are incompatible with sustainable biological control. From an applied perspective, the critical values of body size associated with a potential Hopf bifurcation could serve as risk indicators: if the biological control agent reaches a particular size relative to the pest, the system may enter a dynamic regime characterized by unpredictable oscillations. Such insights could inform the selection of species or strains capable of maintaining the system within a stable regime. Moreover, based on our approach, we present a formula that remains unexplored in empirical ecological research and generates a distinctive dynamic in density trajectories. In particular, the following equation gives rise to a transcritical bifurcation, implying that the system transitions to a strictly positive equilibrium in response to small parameter perturbations48. This bifurcation occurs when body sizes satisfy the following relationship:12\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
