To address one of the central questions of this research What body size relationships ensure the success of biological control? we proposed an indicator that determines pest extinction and resource persistence. This indicator, defined in Eqs. (17) and (19)39,60, establishes quantitative relationships between body sizes and has the potential to be evaluated in field experiments. Figure 4 illustrates two contrasting scenarios. When \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathscr {R}_{0}^{\{CP\}}[m_{C}, m_{R}] > 1$$\end{document}, the system exhibits initial oscillations reflecting the pest’s impact on plant abundance. In contrast, if \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathscr {R}_{0}^{\{CP\}}[m_{C}, m_{R}] < 1$$\end{document}, biological control is immediate, allowing plant abundance to reach its carrying capacity in the short term. Similarly, Fig. 6 shows that when \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathscr {R}_{0}^{\{P\}}[m_{R}, m_{C}, m_{P}] > 1$$\end{document}, biological control is effective, and plant abundance stabilises at its carrying capacity. Conversely, if \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathscr {R}_{0}^{\{P\}}[m_{R}, m_{C}, m_{P}] < 1$$\end{document}, population densities tend to zero, which could eventually lead to resource loss. These results highlight the practical significance of this study by providing quantitative relationships that could be used in pest control programmes. For instance, the global costs associated with managing the diamondback moth (Plutella xylostella) range between 4 and 5 billion USD annually61. Furthermore, since pest responses to global warming vary across latitudes, body-size-based indicators could facilitate local assessments for entomologists and farmers. The integration of these indicators into experimental designs has the potential to optimise management strategies and reduce operational costs54. More broadly, the proposed model enables a quantitative assessment applicable to diverse trophic networks, supporting an abstract yet cost-effective approach to pest control in agricultural and forestry systems56,62.

To investigate top-down mechanisms, we introduce a new indicator that models the trophic cascade effect, as defined in Eq. (19) and illustrated in its three-dimensional representation in Fig. 7. Classic studies on trophic cascades, such as McCann et al.57, have emphasized the importance of weak trophic interactions in stabilizing ecological networks, while Yodzis and Innes22 showed that body size is a key determinant of consumption rates and consumer–resource dynamics. In this work, we build on these foundations by introducing an explicit indicator that models the trophic cascade effect as a function of the relative body sizes of the plant (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$m_R$$\end{document}) and the biological control agent (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$m_P$$\end{document}), defined in Eq. (19) and illustrated in three dimensions in Fig. 7. For the parameter values considered in that figure, we observe that small plant body sizes (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$m_R$$\end{document}) combined with larger sizes of the control agent (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$m_P$$\end{document}) lead to more pronounced cascade effects on plant dynamics, thereby integrating trophic structure and morphological variability into a dynamic framework with potential empirical applicability. This trophic cascade model is consistent with empirical observations from a tritrophic system in the Sierra Nevada, where parasitoids regulate the population of a weevil that preys on the seeds of Hormathophylla spinosa, indirectly benefiting the plant63. Similarly, studies in soybean crops have shown that an increase in spider populations reduces foliar damage by controlling herbivorous insects, whereas their removal leads to greater damage in certain years. These findings confirm the existence of a trophic cascade, where predators indirectly benefit plants by regulating herbivore populations64. The applicability of this model is not necessarily limited to simplified habitats, where herbivore control relies on a single parasitoid species. Instead, it can be extended to agroecological systems, where multiple generalist predators contribute to herbivore regulation. This distinction suggests that trophic cascades in biological control may be stronger but less stable than those found in natural food webs, where regulation is distributed among multiple natural enemies65. From this perspective, we can explore the “enemy hypothesis”, which is widely supported in agricultural systems and posits that greater plant diversity increases the abundance of natural enemies, thereby enhancing herbivore control33,66,67. A key challenge for modeling will be to incorporate trophic cascades that depend on multiple body-size relationships, better reflecting the complexity.

One of the main limitations of this model is the lack of incorporation of evolutionary elements, such as adaptation to body size, which could provide a more integrated view of ecological and evolutionary processes from a tritrophic perspective33. Another parameter that could be incorporated is temperature, to explore its ecological consequences and analyze the relationship between temperature and body size11,68,69. Although chaotic dynamics are beyond the scope of this study, our approach suggests that relationships between body sizes, as presented in Eqs. (11) and (12), could complicate integrated pest management. The mathematical structure of the model has also been explored in the works of Bo Deng70–72, who characterized the chaotic behavior of the system. This has significant implications for pest management, as predator biomass can peak at the onset of a chaotic state70,73, potentially providing valuable insight into understanding these complexities74. On the other hand, recent advances in remote sensing and spatial modeling have significantly improved our understanding of plant diversity and characteristics75–80. In this study, we identify \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$m_R$$\end{document} as the leaf area, which could facilitate the integration of crop information with the proposed indicator \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathscr {R}_{0}$$\end{document}, fostering interdisciplinary collaboration between ecological aspects of tritrophic chains and technological tools. Finally, the modelling proposal presented here is a theoretical exploration, with a strong focus on practical applications aimed at supporting integrated pest management and advancing digital agriculture through data-driven decision-making.
